column1: 17087;instagram;2019-02-19 21:28:27;FALSE;"day 273: ""we won't be shoved under the carpet or buried under the sand""

column2: with not enough literature on the matter. being silenced by others and having to hide behind a mask is common and recovery is a never ending journey that needs awareness
column3: with sharing experiences needing to be prioritised

column1: 17156;instagram;2019-02-19 20:23:43;FALSE;"can we talk a moment about what it means to take seriously the teachings of jesus?
it means that when we see another human being
column2: we see someone who is made in the image of god-this includes the refugee and the immigrant from over the border

column1: taking jesus seriously means that those who wield power give a voice to those who have not had a voice-the silenced women in much of the church
column2: the unborn who are crying out for the chance to live
column3: the sexually abused children under the care of men who say they speak for god
column4: and those who have lived under racismâ€™s suffocating hand.

column1: taking jesus seriously means loving our neighbor as ourselves
column2: which implies that we love who god made us to be and share that love with the person next to us-rejecting body-shaming
column3: comparison-driven culture that celebrates conformity instead of the creative genius in god.

column1: taking jesus seriously means that we lift up the shamed and the broken- embracing the poor
we must stop spouting ideals that are merely that- thoughts in our head with no real-world impact. when the bible tells us to love the lord your god with all your heart
column5: itâ€™s reminding us that love is not just an idea or a feeling. it is with our strength too.

column1: when we put action to the teachings of jesus
column2: when we respond to who he is in us
column3: we embody christ. we become the hands and feet of the savior of the world. his kingdom coming to earth is a real thing
column4: not an abstract concept and he has chosen for us to participate with him in his freedom mission!

column1: letâ€™s let our hearts be broken with what breaks his

column1: 17198;instagram;2019-02-19 20:02:20;FALSE;"here is a national survey on sexual harassment (sh) of medical students in canada published recently by the lancet . this study depicts sh in various forms and perpetrators including patients
column2: peers and faculty. the study collected narrative information about the encounters during medical training
column5: formal and informal reporting and suggestions to improve the learning environment. perpetrators were mostly men and 98% of victims were women. whatâ€™s even more surprising is that most cases go unreported. the environment that follows incorporates sh as normal behaviour. an article published in forbes recently references another study (not yet published) by nayyar et. al. which highlighted that 58% of female surgeons experienced sexual harassment in the previous year alone in united states. the results also showed similar statistics regarding reporting
column6: only 84% of incidents were unreported by women. despite having zero tolerance institutional policies against sh
column7: there is still a lack of support for the students and trainees and the resultant mistrust in the system. it is important to support victims of sh to not isolate them further and identify the perpetrators so the vicious cycle can be interrupted. it is also important to support similar studies around the world and not just the western world
column8: as gender equity is just as important everywhere else. to read the @forbes article: https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucelee/2019/02/16/why-58-of-women-surgeons-experiencing-sexual-harassment-may-hurt-you/#6ebdc35c3975

column1: 17206;instagram;2019-02-19 20:04:07;FALSE;"there's no good way to tell someone you were raped. there's no good way to break it to your friends or family. there's no good way to tell your boss you're having an off day because you laid in bed thinking about how your sheets will feel dirty no matter how many times you wash them; there's no good way to tell the guy you're on a date with that the reason you can't have sex with him is because you're not quite ready to trust a man with your body again. there's no good way to explain that your rapist is the friend of the boy you were seeing for four months
column2: the boy you thought you loved
column3: the boy who told his friends you were just ""good pussy"" to him. there's no good way to tell your therapist you haven't slept right since december
column4: or that your room doesn't feel like yours anymore because that's where it happened and you can't wipes stains like that off the walls. there's no good way to tell someone that you don't feel safe in your skin
column5: that you're terrified of it happening again
column6: that you feel small and afraid every time a man looks at you sideways.

column1: there is no good way to tell my story
column2: but i'll tell it anyway. i was raped on december 1
column3: 2018 by a man who was the friend of the guy i was seeing at the time. i found out today that the pg county state's attorney's office will not take my case because there isn't enough evidence to prove i was the victim of a crime. i hesitated before posting this because it feels invasive and inappropriate to talk about
column4: but i'm hoping that someone will see my story and know that they aren't alone. just because you aren't getting justice in the traditional sense doesn't mean it didn't happen. i will not be swept under the rug; i will not be another statistic about an untested rape kit. i reported my rape. it's real. it happened to me. no one can deny that this happened to me. no one can deny that it happened to you.

column2: come home by 5am at the latest. we had a whole routine.. but anyways
column3: that last party i went to changed a lot. i was drunk
column4: i didn't think i was that drunk... i was talking to a guy who was 18 i had only been 13 for 2 months and 3 days. he was charming
column8: played football and on his way to college soon. we talked about all kinds of stuff. i really liked talking to him. my friend walked away for only a little while before the ""nice guy"" made his move. he got me to my feet and i realized how drunk i was i'm assuming he had to carry me up the stairs cause i don't even remember stepping on the first step completly... i just remember everything that happened after i was trapped... in his grip on that bed. screaming felt impossible... moving was impossible... in a month from today it will make it  2 years ago from the day you hurt me worse than any other guy ever had...i was raped when i was 13..not able to hardly move the next morning..i tried killing myself not long after... i was taking a pregnancy test crying in the bathroom at 13 terrified that i might get something not knowing who he was or how many others he'd done this to. but it guess the worst part of all was knowing i couldn't tell anyone... today i decided to tell all of you because you've all been so supportive and i feel as though through this whole journey you should know were a big portion of my issues came from. #metoo i didn't report cause i was drunk i was 13 no one would believe someone who was drunk and doesn't even know the guy name and snuck out to get there... it's been 2 years... my parents still don't know and i'm owkay with that... #whyididntreport";;en;#metoo

column2: independence and  self-assurance  to the extreme unapologetic attitude and fiercely support collective upliftment.  i am a figurative artist working in mixed media and collaged fabrics on canvas and paper. i borrow  images and motifs from european classical and mid -century artists (like picasso and others)  and south african contemporary and master artists (like kentridge and adam alberts and othes) and juxtapose them with traditional african  and  european fabrics  to create  unique hybrid of female figures set in imagined  settings
column4: derived from the phrase â€˜cloud 9â€™ where one is said to experience euphoria and/or familiar settings like the south african landscapes  painted by  pierneef or having tea parties and picnics amongst plants like the indigenous blue daisy and aloes as well as wild animals.  the result is a hybridization  of styles and motifs and imagery that  represent  a new identity of african women based on the mixing of the past and present socio-political and cultural influences of african and european origins. ""

column1: fixed it!  so from a legal and human rights perspective
column2: my version is more accurate.  how on earth
column4: do we have it so reversed??
and the public are unaware of the rights of birthing people.  yes
column5: all three of those groups.  most people believe that the doctor ""ultimately"" has the right to make decisions about birth.

column2: this contributes to a lot of problems: skyrocketing induction and c-section rates
column5: i'll say it--even more reinforcement of truly messed up cultural beliefs and norms around how women and mothers are valued.  which is to say
column6: not very much.  the birth room is where prejudice
column10: and all kinds of other -isms converge on individuals at their absolute most vulnerable.

column1: how do we flip that on its head?  we start with education.  i'll tell you what
column2: it pissed me off when i found out after the fact that i had always had the right to say ""no"" to an induction being pushed on me.  i always thought i would have advocated for myself that much more confidently if i had known just how strong my rights were and what they were based on.

column1: if you can learn to travel light
and only pack what must be onyour own shoulders
if you can put just the right things you were meant to carry for just the few people for whom you can do so well
you will go farther in your relationships than you could admit now.
stop thinking you can change the world
your strong shoulders are still fragile.
maybe that kind of love can step from one soul to another.
maybe that kind of example could set someone else free.
and travel well with eyes wide open and record all of it so that you can remember
your heart can travel farther than your feet ever could.
let the real joy find you.

column1: 17639;instagram;2019-02-19 14:32:35;FALSE;"when i first decided to share my story and write my book i was nervous and thought nobody would care. i struggled with the idea of seeing myself as a survivor and a advocate. i struggled with seeing myself as the woman god created me to be. i  didnâ€™t think i could do it alone. all that changed when my brave 9 year old joined me in writing the book and inspired me with her words of wisdom. with her opening up to me in the book she also let me know she was aware of all the things i had been through bc she was right there. this opened my eyes to the reflection that i saw when i looked at her. she was watching and listening and it effected her
column2: but i could not see it due to my own past traumas. now life is different
column3: and we are happy and safe. i share this story to encourage you to look at this picture and see that all things that are meant to break you
column4: can also be a breaking point for you to have change for the better. i changed my perspective on life and now i look at things from a optimistic standpoint
column5: itâ€™s one day at a time

column1: i never really told anyone about how deep my trauma was.
yesterday i managed to write about it in my post.
writing helps me deal with it.
and i was scared and ready for people to attack me...
i got only love & support from youâ™¥ï¸â™¥ï¸â™¥ï¸
i received amazing reactions in the comments underneath the post but as well dozens of beautiful private messages.
thank you for sharing your stories with me.
each and every one of you touched my soulğŸ¥°
and you know whatâ€™s the funniest thing about it?
my entire life i was told that showing my weaknesses will shut the door of opportunity for me.
sharing my story opened so many doors and hearts yesterdayğŸ¤—
i remember what my work colleague
column2: who saw me cry at work because of the man who mobbed me

column1: â€šjust donâ€™t cry in front of him. it will make him feel more powerful.â€™
i know that she meant well..
but how strange this world is that we tell each other to numb the pain and to cover the tears even when someone mistreats us.
tears are a natural reaction of our organisms to deal with trauma.
they help us get the negative emotions out of our organisms.
and i donâ€™t mean here being a wining person that is always complaining.
if someone breaks your human rights
it should not be about covering up our tears but about preventing those painful situations from happening.
i promise to myself i will never let anyone mistreat me againğŸ’ª
i managed to get to hungerburgbahn on saturdayâ™¥ï¸
my boyfriend had to hold me tight in his arms
column2: because i got a panic attack before entering the train.

column1: i was afraid that the work colleague who mobbed me might be inside.
so my boyfriend had to come in first and check the whole compartment...
i felt so guilty of the way i behaved...
no one has ever said that fear is something logical.
it is a horrible mental trap.
but i managed to get up there.
and the moment i looked at innsbruck from above i gained a new perspective and could finally breathe.
